{"/service/ndnp/mb/batch_mb_allspice_ver01/data/sn83020847/00517171062/1927010601/0013.xml":{"full_text":"MONEY and BUSINESS\nThe Business Year\nThe moderate slackening: of busi\nness activity In December has as yet\nproved nothing except that the pace\nof midsummer and early fall was too\nrapid to be kept up. Whether this re\ntardation Is to be succeeded by a re\nvival early In the year or whether It\nis the first stage of a continuing slight\nrecession la not a subject about which\nthe New Year business forecasters\ncould be expected to speak with as\nsurance. A year ago the prophets\nforesaw a contraction of activity be\nfore the end of 1826, brought about\nby a decline in building operations and\nin motor car production, and per\nhaps by an excess of instalment\nselling. These prophecies were not\nfulfilled and 1926 exceeded the most\noptimistic expectations. The current\nprophecies are predominantly optlm\nistie. Yet if the decline in building\nwas not pronounced in 1926, It may\nbecome so in 1927, and the curtail\nment of motor car output which was\navoided by the pulsing prospe: ity of\n1926, can more scientifically be\nbrought within the range of 1927 fore\ncasts, particularly when the unsatis\nfactoriness of the agricultural eco\nnomic situation is taken into consid\neration. The danger inherent in in\ni' stalment selling can be tested only If\nthere is a business recession.\nThe last week of the year is usual\nly quiet in wholesale markets, and the\nlast week of 1926 is believed to have\nseen about the same amount of whole\nsale and retail trade as the corre\nr sponding week of 1926. In the major\nindustry, steel, new business In the\nlast week of 1926 was less promising\nthan at the previous year's end. Steel\ni production Is now averaging around\ni 72 per cent of capacity and no in\ncrease of output is looked for this\nmonth. Steel ingot production has\nbeen so markedly in excess es that a\nyear ago that the tapering off at the\ni year's close will not adversely affect\nthe record. The average price of fln\nished steel stands at the same level\nas a year ago, but pig iron l is con\nj siderably lower.\nS; Railroad car loadings, which are the\nbest barometer of business activity,\ni have for two weeks totaled less than\nj in the corresponding weeks of 1925.\nBut for phenomenal coal traffic, this\nj decline would have occurred three\nweeks earlier than it did. But when\nIt is considered that in every week\nj from February 13 to December 4. the\nweekly report of car loadings showed\na gain over the same week of 1925,\nthe change of direction is more im\nl portant as an indication of tendency\ni\u2019 than alarming in itself. The collapse\nof automobile output in December is\nagain evidenced in Detroit employ\ni ment figures, which stood at 87,842\nduring Christmas week, in compari-\nI ion with 129,104 for the same week\nt of 1925.\nHenry Ford\u2019s opinion that the in\n-1 dustries of the country have been\nj falling into overproduction Is not\nI shared by the United States depart\nment of commerce. Even the motor In\nf: dustry is declared by government ex\nperts to have kept its increased out\nput on the safe side of reckless ex\npansion. There is still talk about an\nI overproduction of cotton, but no one\nI can say how far the cotton grower\n'1 should be blamed for this. Unless it\nis shown that there would have been\nsurplus on a normal yield, the south\nern farmers cannot be justly cen\nsured for the acreage planted to cot\nton.\nThroughout the country, according\nto government statistics for January,\ni 1925, there was a reduction of 5 per\ncent in the acreage of all harvested\ncrops between 1919 and 1924, The\nj average value of farm lands on March\n1> 1826, was 276.46 an acre, compared\nj with *107.89 In 1920\u2014a loss of 30 per\ncent. Massachusetts Is one of the\nWEEKLY REVIEW\nOF BOND MARKET\nij\nPrices at Top Level at New\nYear s With Broad Action\nExpected Trading Quiet\non Tight Money\n[By th\u00bb Associated Press.]\nNew York, Jan. 2\u2014With prices of\nmost c'asses of bonds, excepting rail\nroad obligations, standing at the high\nest levels since the beginning of the\nWorld war, the new year opens aus\npiciously for the Investment market.\nAside from minor Interruptions, a\nsteady forward movement has been in\nprogress since the early fall, with\nevery Indication that it will be carried\nover Into 1927. Normally, a large vol\nume of reinvestment buying is counted\non to sustain the market early in Jan\nuary and this year it is expected that\nthem will be the added impetus of\nrelaxing money rates when dividend\nand Interest disbursements, as well as\nholiday funds, pour back to the finan\ncial oenters.\nBuying activities In the final week\nof 1928, however, were curbed by the\ntraditional tightening of credit inci\ndent to the year-end settlements. The\nreservoir of surplus funds was deplet\ned by the calling' of bank loans In\nlarge volume and a further hardening\nof money rates. As a result, the mar\nket ended the year in a quiet trading\nmood, apparently waiting for the next\nturn in the money eltuatlon. A reduc\ntion of the New York Federal Reserve\nrediscount rate early this year would\nnot be surprising.\nTear's Issues at $7,000,000,004\nAlong with the contraction of trad\ning activity last week, came the ex\npected curtailment of new financing\nwhich Invariably marks the period be\ntween the holidays. New bond offer\nings approximated U*. 000,000, com\npared with $60,000,000 in the week pre\nceding Christmas. These were suffi\ncient, however, to swell the year\u2019s to\ntal to a new high record around $7,-\n000.900,000, including capital flotation*\nof all kinds.\nForeign obligations, which scored a\nremarkable recovery during the year,\n\u2022continued to run true to form last\nstates where the value of farm land\nis now greater than in 1920.\nWhile the year's volume of indus\ntrial production and distribution at\ntained a new high record, not all sta\ntistical comparisons between 1925 and\n1926 were in favor of the latter year.\nFarm crops for the year 1925 are\nestimated to have had a value of\n*8,949,321,000; \"for last year the value\nis tentatively placed at \u201d7,801,313,000.\nThe wheat crop was greater, but the\ncorn, oats, rye and barley crops were\nreduced, and this, in the main, with\nout offsetting rise In prices. A com\nfortable surplus in the world's wheat\ncrop is now assured, and, while the\nloss of 6 points in Friday's wheat\ntrading at Chicago wad~due to specu\nlative operations, an easy wheat mar\nket is confidently expected.\nRailroad net earnings made a no\ntable gain in 1926 over 1925. Bank\nclearings showed an increase for the\nwhole year, though falling off in the\nlast eight weeks. The par value of\nbond sales in 1926 was lower and the\nsales of stock were not quite up to\nthe level of 1925. Merchandise ex\nports were slightly lower, but cotton\nexports were slightly increased. Cot\nton consumption in the United States\nrose to 6.665,000 bales from 6,338.000,\nand the cotton textile industry had a\nbetter year, which was reflected in\nthe increased employment figures for\nNew England.\nPerhaps the most remarkable phe\nnomenon of the year was\" the stability\nor actual decline of commodity prices\nin a period of eager prosperity. This\nis believed to have been due to con\nservative buying policies, made pos\nsible by prompt railroad deliveries,\nbut the absence of speculative buying\nprobably indicates also that competi\ntion was still fairly active in the av\nerage industry. In other words, while\ntrade was vigorous, production ca\npacity was generally ahead of de\nmand by a fair margin.\nOne price index stood at $187,746 in\nDecember 1, 1926, compared with\n*198,456 on December 1, 1925. The\nUnited States bureau of labor statis\ntics and the national industrial con\nference board report a drop of be\ntween 5 and 6 per cent in living\ncosts during the year. The former\norganization puts the cost of living\nin December at 73 per cent above\nwhat it was in 1913, and t\u2019--> latter\nputs it at 65 or 66 per cent above\nwhat it was in July, 1914. While the\nmethods of computation are different,\nthere is little discrepancy. The peak\nof the increase in living costs came\nin June, 1920, when the index was\n116.5 per cent above 1913.\nAlthough money rates on the stock\nexchange were fractionally higher in\n1926, the year was one of cheap and\nabundant credit. The country now\nhas, for the first time in its history,\nsays Col L. P. Ayres, \"a sufficient\nsupply Of liquid credit to finance\nsimultaneously a period of industrial\nprosperity and one cx nctive security\nspeculation.\u201d Belief in the continu\nance of an easy and ample money\nfund for speculative uses is the basis\no:i which predictions of a fairly strong\nstock market rest- A depression, or\na bear market, Col Ayres observes,\nhas not occurred ir. 50 years except\nafter a period of rapidly rising rates\nfor short-term credit and usually an\nactual shortage. How the market,\nbolstered by ample credit, would be\naffected by a considerable decline in\nbusiness is open to conjecture. The\nimmense addition in the past two\nyears to the country\u2019s store of capital\nwill presumably lower interest rates\nstill further unless the expansion in\nbusiness or in building continues; but\nthis development, of course, would in\nitself tend to keep securities prices\nhigh. It is an interesting point that\nthe New York Times finds a large\nnumber in the financial community,\nwho, while taking publicly a bullish\nposition regarding 1926,' are privately\nbearish.\nweek, many of them climbing to new\nhigh records. French government and\nrailroad issues were strengthened by\nthe success of the currency \u201cprestab\nilization\" plan and the prospects for a\nsolution of the war debt problem this\nyear. Belgian, German and other Eu\nropean bonds continued to attract\nbuyers because of their high yield and\nthe general improvement in financial\nconditions.\nUnited States government obligations\nalso attained new peak prices as the\nyear drew to a close. Buying was stim\nulated by the growing- attractiveness of\nthe bonds for gilt-edged Investments\nbecause of the reduction in the gov\nernment debt and the possibility of a\nlarger treasury surplus.\nSLUMP IN BUILDING\nACTIVITY SINCE 1925\nPittsfield, Jan. 2\u2014Building permits\nissued last year by Inspector John H.\nFlynn totaled $2,707,606, as compared\nwith $3,244,000 in 1926. In 1926 per\nmit', ;vere Issued for 80 single houses,\n17 double houses and one \u201cfour-deck\ner, while 298 permits were issued for\ngarages costing $159,155, England\nBrothers expended $316,000 on the ad\ndition to their North-street depart\nment store block, and the Berkshire\nLife Insurance company building on\nWest street, now under construction,\nis to cost $250,000. The General Elec\nh\u00abns?i npan Ls* pended WOO.OOO i n new\nT h c \u00b0\u00bbtly dwellings\nwere those of James W. Wasbburne\non spadina parkway, Frederick C\nPeach on High street and E. 1,. Bliss\u2019\non C-rofut street, eat*\u2019/ around $25,000,\nAMERICAN-BELCIAN\nCOPPER INTERESTS JOIN\n[By the Associated Press.]\nNew York, Dec. so\u2014Announcement\nwas mude today here that, ns a normal\ndevelopment of the situation created\nby Copper Exporters, lnc., in the ex\nport market, the Anaconda group, Cal\numet Hecla and United Verde com\npanies. on the one side, and Katanga\nand Societe Generals Metaiurgique\nd\u2019Hoboken on the other, have decided\nto merge their continental selling or\nganization*. The results of this will\nnot only be a practical economy in the\nadministration of these sales organize\ntjons, it 1* said, but will reinforce the\nalready close co-operation in continen\ntal market* between these American\ntod Belgian producer*.\nTHE SPRINGFIELD WEEKLY REPUBLICAN: SPRINGFIELD, MASS.: THURSDAY, JANUARY 6, 1927\nTRADE DECLINES\nIN ACTIVITY AND\nVOLUME IN 1926\nBut Continues Higher Than\nFive-Year Average\nMetal Trade Centers Re\nport Boom Conditions\nBoston, Dec. 30\u2014(AP)\u2014The coming\nof the new year finds factories active\nand retail distributors of merchandise\nprogressing in large volume, accord\ning to monthly review of Industrial\nand financial conditions in the New\nEngland district by the Federal Re\nserve bank of Boston. Business activ\nity is at a lower rate than a year ago\nboth in this district and in the country\nas a whole but is somewhat higher\nthan the five-year average, the report\nsets forth.\n\"Industry starts the year 1927 with\nfactories quite active,\u201d the report be\ngins, \"with retail distribution of mer\nchandise in large volume, with prices\nof basic raw materials having shown\na decline for about 18 months and with\nloans of commercial banks at nearly\nthe largest amount on record and\nmoney rates fairly firm.\nI.ess Activity than Year Ago\n\"Business activity at the beginning\nof 1927, however, is at a lower rate\nthan a year ago. both in this district\nand in the country as a whole. In both\neases the current rate of activity is\nsomewhat higher than the average\nmaintained during the past five years.\n\"Business conditions in the country\nas a whole were extraordinarily stable\nand free from fluctuation in 1926. but\nin New England there was a recession\nin activity during the summer months,\nfollowed by a partial recovery in the\nautumn.\n\u201cThe average Massachusetts factory\ndid not have quite as many people on\nits payroll in 1926 as in the previous\nyear, but the average weekly earn\nings of the employes were slightly\nhigher than in 1925.\n\"The total value of business in the\nleading New England textile centers\nduring 1926 was less than in 1925, and\nbut little better than in 1924. The im\nportant shoe cities, on the other hand,\nreported the largest value of business\nin 1926 for several years. Metal trade\ncenters reported the largest value of\nbusiness since war times.\nDollar Value of Trade I.ess\n\"The decline in bas'c raw material\nprices since the summer of 1925 has\nbeen an important factor in the busi\nness situation and has tended to re\nduce the dollar value of trade, as dis\ntinct from the physical volume of\ntrade. Some shrinkage in inventory\nvalues has been caused by declining\nprices, and the value of check pay\nments has also been affected.\n\u201cRetail distribution of merchandise\nthrough the New England department\nstores, and in fact, through depart\nment stores in the entire country, was\nlarger in 1926 than in any previous\nNEW YCRK STOCK MARKET\nTotal sales of stocks, 1,458,400 shares. Averages:\nTwenty industrials, 143.38; Tuesday, 143.33; week ago,\n145.50; year ago, 142.84; high, 1926, 148.89; low, 1926,\nThe high and low prices for 1026 in the first two columns\nare carried to the previous close.\nPrev. 3920 Div. Net\nHigh. Low. in Sales. High. Low. Close, ch\u2019e.\n72 43 ABRAHAM AST 500 69 66V* 06%\u20142\n336 99% 6 Adams Express 100 124 124 124\n22 8 Adv Rurnely 760 10% 10 10%+\nG 5% 28% do pr TOO 34% 33% 34%+ 1\nAlum a.' V- 3\n16 7% fAjax Rubber 300 9% 0% J)%+\ndo rts 500 1-16\n155 131 7 AU-Am Cable 3 300 145% 145 145\n148% 106 6 All Ch Dye 9,300 137 335% 135%\u2014\n122% 118% 7 do pr 300 121% 120% 120%\u2014\n94% 78Vi 6 Allis Chalmers 100 89 89 89\n22% Amai Leather 400 17% 16% 17%+\n32% 24% 2 Amerada Corp 1,300 32 31% 31\n34% 9 Am Agri Chem 400 13% 13 13%\n4d 14% Am Bank Note 50ft 42% 42% 42%+\n58% 55 3 *do pr 10 56 56% 56%\n38% 20% Am Beet Sugar 200 25% 25% 25%+ 1%\n34% 16 Am Bosch Mag 600 17% 16% 17%+ 1\n50 30Vi 2 Am Brown Bov 500 39 39 39%+\n63% 38% 2 American Can 8,400 48% 47% 48\n121 I db P r \u00ab00 129% 128% 128%\u2014\n114% 91 6 Am Car A Fdy 200 100% 100% 100%+\n130% 120% 7 do pr 100 128% 128% 128%\u20141%\n10% 4% Am Drug Synd 100 9% 9% 9%\u2014\n340 105% 6 Am Express 100 128 128 128\n42% 14% Am For Pow 10,900 \u00a32% 21% 22\n98 79 7 do pr 100 89 89 89\n37% 7 Am Hide A L 100 9 9 9\n