%-\n20V 7 Cent leather (981 9% 9*4 *4\n63*4 43% do pr 1.600 37J* 56 57*J+2\n8% 7 do etfs 1.21X* 8% 8% BX4 1\n54% 50 do !t>. ctfe LOOM TvS** 56 36*4+\n325 t t'l% Ctett Rib Mills W 6) 11% 11% 11 *4-1\n78*4 \"7\u2019,4 3b Ceim de Pasco 1.100 62 \u00ab1%\n49*4 38*4 4 Ortomteed 3.300 43*4 42 42*-,+\n28 8% Chsndlsr Cbrv* 600 9% 8 9*4+4\n20*4 B*4 do pr lot> 28 22% 22%+\n17854 lit i ones Ohio 1,800 162% 161 *4 .181%\nyear for which records are available.\nThe increase in New England depart\nment store sales in 1926 as compared\nwith 1925 was entirely due to larger\nsales on charge and Instalment ac\ncounts. there being no Increase report\ned in the total volume of cash sales.\n\"There wag not as much building ac\ntivity in New England during the\npast year as in 1925, but with that ex\nception there was the largest volume\nof building in New England on record.\n\"Both total deposits and total loans\nof member banks in New England av\neraged higher In 1926 than In the pre\nvious year. The growth in deposits\nwas even more noticeable in the so\ncalled country banks than in the\nbanks In Boston.\n\u201cMoney rates on the whole were\nsomewhat firmer than In 1925. con\ntinuing the upward trend in effect\nsince the third quarter of 1924.\"\nBANKERSTOPAY^ $115\nFOR VICTOR\u2019S STOCK\nNew York, Jan. 3\u2014(AP) \u2014.Speyer\nCo. J. W. Seligman Co. bankers,\ntoday announced that they were pre\npared to exercise on Thursday their\noption on controling interests in the\ncapital stock of the Victor Talking\nMachine company, recently acquired\nfrom Eldridge R. Johnson, founder\nand president. A special meeting of\nstockholders has been called for\nThursday to discuss a plan for re\ncapitalization, which is regarded as a\nsimple matter in view of the fact that\nthe company has no funded debts and\nbut little preferred stock outstanding.\nUnder the terms of the option the\nbankers have agreed to make the\nsame offer which Mr Johnson receiv\ned to minority stockholders, namely,\nto buy their holdings at *lls a share.\nThe stock is now quoted on the New\nYork Curb market at around *152 a\nshare, having advanced more than *3O\nsince the option agreement was made\npublic.\nCOAST BRICKLAYERS\nTO GET sll DAILY\nSan Francisco, Jan. 3\u2014(AP)\nBricklayers will receive a minimum\nof *ll a day under the new wage\nscale fixed by the wage board for the\nSan Francisco building industry, ef\nfective today. The General Contrac\ntors\u2019 association has agreed to accept\nthe new scale. The old minimum for\nbricklayers was *lO.\nNew minimum rates for carpenters,\npainters and electrical workers was\nfixed at *9, a raise of a dollar, while\niron workers and plasterers draw *ll,\nas compared to the old rate of *lO.\nLaborers generally received a 50 cent\nincrease from the old scale of *4.50\nto *5.\nNATIONAL bank\nCALL ANNOUNCED\nWashington, Jan. 3\u2014(AP)\u2014The\ncontroller of the currency today is\nsued a call for the condition of all na\ntional banks at the close of business\non Friday, December 31.\nBy the Associated Press\n123.11. Twenty railroads, 125.58; Tuesday, 125.66;\nweek ago, 126.16; year ago, 116.84; high, 1926, 128.73;\nlow, 1926, 105.88.\nPvev. 3926 Div. Ket\nHigh. Low. in\u00bb Sales. High. Low. Close, ch'e.\n11*4 4*4 Ch! Alton 100 454 474 47 s\n1814 6% do pr 100 714 7% 7%+ *4\n1214 7% Chi &Gt West 200 8 B*4 8*4+14\n31% 16*4 do pr 200 24 23% 23%\u2014 *4\n14% BV4 Clll M&St P 200 9 9% 9%+ *4\n24 14% do pr 100 19*4 19% 19*4+ '4\n1 4 7% do ctf 300 9% 9% 9*4+ *4\n88% 65% 4 Chi N West 900 7914 79 79\n126% 318% 7 do pr 100 125% 123% 12514+1\n128\u20184 94% 6 Chi Pr.eti Tool 100 120% 120% 120%\n71% 40% Chi R 1 A Pac 1,900 70 69 69%+\n*8 83 6 do 6% pr 600 9574 95*4 05%\u2014\n108 96 7 do 7% pr 100 103*4 103% 103*4+ *4\n37.% 48 CSPMiO* 35 55 55 55 +5\n66*4 45% 2.40 g Childs Co 1,500 5154 51 51*4+\n.\u2019l6*4 30 2*4 Chile Copper 1,300 347* 34% 34*4\n63% 29% 1.20 Christie Brown 400 35*4 34\u2019% 35*4+1%\n54% 28% 3 Chrysler Mot 60,900 43*4 42% 43*4+1