2 do ctfe 9*H\u00bbt 38% 38 38\n03% \u00aboV*j 4 Gen Kv Signal 1,500 84% 83 84 +l%\n105 503 0 do p\u00bb%t* 110 104 104 104\n78% H% Gimbel Rrt>\u00bb 300 41% 41%\n25% 13% 2 GUdden Co 2.\u00abX\u00bb0 21%\nMU 41% Gold Dust Co 45 44 45 4 2\n70% :i9% 4 Goodrich 44% 43% 44\n1t,94% 7 do pref 40\u00bb 05 95 93\n109% 96% 7 Goodyear pf 1/m m 99% 90%-f\n86% 16% Granby Mining s<\u00bb* 34% 34% 54%\n57% 18 1% Gt No Or ctfe 200 19% 19% 19%\n84% 68% ft Gt North pref 2500 80% 60 60%+\nFISK RUBBER\u2019S\nEARNINGS SHRINK\nReports Net Profits of $3,-\n354,431 For Year Ended\nOctober 31, $6,108,905\nPrevious Year\nNew' York, Dec. 29\u2014(AP)\u2014Fisk\nRubber company reports net profit of\n*3,354,431 for the year ended October\n31 after reserve of *1,000,000 for con\ntingencies and other charges, equal to\n*2.23 a share on the common, after\nfull year\u2019s dividends on ail classes of\npreferred stocks and management\nstocks. In the preceding year net\nprofit was *6,108,905 or *5.86 a share\non the common then outstanding.\nSays 1927 Outlook Good\nThe annual report of the Fisk Rub\nber comiiany for the fiscal year end\ning October 31. 1926, show an operat\ning profit after depreciation, but be\nfore interest and taxes, amounting to\napproximately *6,000,000. The gross\nsales of the company reached a figure\nof upward of *68,000,000. The direc\ntors report to the stockholders that\nthe outlook for 1927 is favorable and\nthat satisfactory profits may be looked\nforward to.\nThe statement accompanying the\nfinancial report is partly as follows:\n\"The tire industry in 1926 contend\ned against a drastic decline in the\nprice of its two chief raw materials\u2014\ncrude rubber and cotton. Regardless\nof this condition, gross sales less re\nturns and allowances for the vear,\namounted to *68.051,739.43 and operat\ning profits after depreciation but be\nfore interest and taxes were approxi\nmately *6,000,000. As 1925 was a year\nof inflation in crude rubber prices and\n1926 a year of deflation, normal earn\ning power may be more nearly regard\ned as the average of the two years.\n\"Inventories as of October 31 were\ntaken on a conservative basis from\nwhich is deducted an amount set aside\nof *1,000,000 as a reserve against pos\nsible future contingencies.\n\"The major part of the contingency\nreserve of *1,500,000, set aside last\nyear, has been used for the cancela\ntion and readjustment of fabric con\ntracts applicable to future years.\n\u201cDuring the current fiscal year the\ndividend:, on preferred and manage\nments stocks accumulated prior to Oc\ntober 31, 1025. were paid or provided\nfor in full, by the issue of *4,467,500\npar value 7 per cent first preferred\nconvertible stock and by the payment\nof *660,264 in cash. Dividends for the\ncurrent year amounting to *1,511,150\nwere paid in cash.\n\"The company is in a strong finan\ncial condition. Total current assets at\nthe end of the year were $36,995,272,\n\u25a0and current liabilities *2,949,825, giv\ning a ratio of current assets to cur\nrent liabilities of 12% to 1.\n\"The outlook is good for a satisfac\ntory volume of business in 1927.\nStabilized raw material markets\nshould assure satisfactory profits on\nthat business.\u201d\nSTOCK PRICES RISE\nAS 1926 CONCLUDES\nSigns of Bullish Enthusiasm\nRetained Despite Year-End\nSelling to Establish Tax\nLosses\nNew York, Dec. 31\u2014<;a.v>\\ \u2014The\nyear in the stock market passed out\ntoday on a tide of rising prices which 1\nengulfed an early reaction resulting\nfrom a widespread readjustment of j\nspeculative holdings. The final session\nof 1926 was also marked by the usual\nyear-end selling to establish tax losses,\nbut the market generally retained the\nsigns of bullish enthusiasm which\nhave characterized trading for the\npast two years.\nAt the closing gong on the New\nYork Stock Exchange brokers on the\nfloor began their usual celebration to\nmark the end of a year which has\nbeen unusually prosperous for them.\nBands flared from the galleries, my\nriads of toy balloons floated to the\nlofty ceiling and a shower of confetti\nand ticker tape spread a white blanket\nseveral inches deep over the famous\nfloor on which the \"bulls'' and \u2018'bears''\nof Wall street have staged their\ngreatest fights.\nAtchison and other high-grade rail\nroad shares, whose holders are ex\npected to receive more generous divi\ndend treatment next year, led the final\nupturn in prices today, while Baldwin,\nj General Motors and United States\ni Steel, ranking at the head of the in\ndustrials, lost ground.\nTRAVELERSINSURANCE\nOVER $1,021,000,000\nHartford, Ct., Jan. 2 (AP) \u2014The\nTravelers\u2019 Insurance company, in a\npreliminary annual statement issued\ntoday, reports it has joined the circle\nof *1,000.000,000 life insurance com\npanies. The new life insurance written\nby the Travelers in 1926 will bring the\ntotal to a sum in excess of *1,021,00,-\n000, tile report shows this being a\ngain of *39,650,000 over the new paid\nlife insurance of the company in 1925.\nAs a further reflection of the pros\n-1 perity which ruled in the nation dur-\nI ing 1926, the report continues, the to\ntal premiums for the Travelers' com\nj panles will be more than *160,840.000,\nwhich with earnings on investments\nI will raise the total income of the com\npanies to more than *179,960,000. The\npremium gain is *23,450,000 over that\nof 1925.\nBABSON GIVES $1,200,000\nTO INSTITUTE ENDOWMENT\nWellesley, Jan. 3\u2014(AP) \u2014Roger\nBabson, statistician and founder of\nthe Babson Statistical institute, has\ngiven *1,200.000 to the endowment\nfund of his organization, it was an\nnounced today.\nNEW YORK STOCK MARKET\nPrev. 1926 Div. Set\nHigh. Ixjw. In Sales. High Lew. Close, ch'e.\n113% 89 8 Gt West Sug 3,600 11,3% 112 112 4-\n118% 108% 7 do pref* 320 120 118% 120 4-1%\n34% 9% Greer Can C 300 31% 31 31%+1%\n41% 25% Gulf M A N 300 36 35% 35%\u2014\n93% 51% 5 Gulf Sta Stl 400 55 53% 55 +l%\n60% 45 HANNA 1 PF* 200 59% 59% 59% \u20