also were the largest on record j\nmounting to $350,000,000 against *275,-\n000,000 last year.\nSecurities of more than 800 com- j\npanies were admitted to trading. The I\ntotal number of stocks and bonds list- j\nfed at the end of the year was about\n1375, compared with 1100 at the end of\n1925. The total par value of stocks\nnow dealt in is more than *14.000.000\nin addition to 250,000,000 snares with-\nout par vaiue.\nProtective Features Added\nAdoption of a new constitution con-\ntaininf added provisions in the inter\nest of the purchaser of Curb securities\nwas the most important step taken by\nthe exchange during the year, acoord\ning to President David U. Page. List\ning marginal and membership require\ni ments were made more stringent, j\nMany issues of unknown intrinsic j\nI value were stricken from the trading\nlist.\nA tremendous increase in bond\ntrading made it necessary to allot\nlarger quarters to that section of the\nmarket, and record-breaking clear\nances also demanded enlargement of\ni the clearing house facilities.\nEleven cities in the United States\nand Canada were receiving the Curb\nticker service at the end of the year.\nI Buffalo and Toronto were added to the\nchain m 1926 and plans are under con\nsideratlon for extending the service to\nMontreal as well as to several other\ni larger cities in the United States.\nThe membership list of the Curb re\nmained near 550, with several seats\nj changing hands around the record\nhigh price of *37,500, established in\ni December, 1925.\nREFUSES DISMISSAL\nOF MERGER PROTEST\nCincinnati, 0., Jan. 3\u2014(AP)\nUnited States District Judge Smith\nHickenlooper today over-ruled a mo\ntion by the Cleveland, Cincinnati\nSt Louis Railway company and the\nNew York Central Railroad company,\nasking dismissal of the suit of John\nD. Jackson, a minority stockholder,\nto prevent the absorption of the Big\nFour railroad by the New York Cen\ntral.\nNEW IORK STOCK MARKET V\nPrev. 1926 Div. .*|v\nHigh. Low. In ft. Sal